# Agent Instructions

This project is an Intropy **loader block**: a .NET worker that subscribes to a system topic and
loads each event into an external system through an outbound connector. It is a complete, runnable
integration on its own, and also composes into a larger system via a sibling SystemHost.

## Project overview

- Framework: .NET 10, ASP.NET Minimal API worker, Intropy Framework Blocks (send pipeline)
- Block kind: loader
- App id / component name: `{{ .name }}`
- Subscribes: topic `{{ .subscribesTopic }}` on pub/sub component `pubsub`
- Loads into: external system `{{ .targetSystem }}` via the `{{ .connector }}` connector — Dapr
  binding component `binding.{{ .connector }}` (transport chosen at `intropy system create`)

## The two run modes (one binary, swapped components folder)

The worker always binds to **stable Dapr component names** — `pubsub` and `binding.{{ .connector }}`.
What those names resolve to is decided entirely by which components folder the Dapr sidecar loads
(`--resources-path`):

- **Standalone** (`task run`): `./local/dapr-components/` — `pubsub` is `pubsub.in-memory`,
  `binding.{{ .connector }}` is `bindings.localstorage` writing to `./local/storage/outbound`.
- **Under a SystemHost**: the run backend generates a components folder and points the sidecar at it,
  so `pubsub` becomes Redis and `binding.{{ .connector }}` becomes the connector's real transport.
  The code is identical in both; do not hard-code anything that differs between them here.

## Important files

- `Program.cs` — host + DI: Dapr client, `AddIntropyFramework`, the connector `IFileAdapter`, and the
  load pipeline registered as `ISendPipeline<Context>`.
- `Configuration/Constants.cs` — the stable component names (`pubsub`, `binding.{{ .connector }}`)
  and the subscribed topic. These must match on both sides of the folder swap.
- `Process/` — the send pipeline (deserialize → validate → transform → serialize → write to
  connector) built from framework Send blocks: `LoadPipeline` (the pipeline), `LoadPipelineBuilder`
  (fluent builder), `ServiceCollectionExtensions` (`AddLoadPipeline`), and one step class per file
  under `Steps/`. Idempotency / business-incident routing are intentionally omitted from this light
  scaffold.
- `Ingest/Endpoints.cs` — `POST /subscribe` (the Dapr subscription) and `POST /publish` (a standalone
  helper that seeds the subscribed topic).
- `Model/Messages.cs` — placeholder payload records; replace with the system's real contract.
- `local/dapr-components/` — the standalone components (`pubsub`, `binding.{{ .connector }}`).
- `Taskfile.yml` — `task run`, `task publish`, `task clean`.

## Scaffold record

`.intropy/scaffold.json` carries this component's edge intent in its `topology` section (block kind,
subscribed topic, connector). `intropy system create` reads the records of all sibling components to
generate a wired SystemHost — do not edit the `topology` section by hand; re-scaffold instead.

The folder name, csproj name, and Dapr app-id must all stay `{{ .name }}` — the SystemHost resolves
this project by that convention (`../{{ .name }}/{{ .name }}.csproj`).

## Build and run

```bash
task build        # dotnet build
task run          # dapr run --resources-path ./local/dapr-components -- dotnet run
task publish      # publish a sample event onto the subscribed topic (while `task run` is up)
```

## Wiring into a system

From the parent directory that holds all component folders:

```bash
intropy system create -n <system-name>
dotnet run --project <SystemName>.SystemHost -- check
```
